Network topology defines the physical or logical layout of how devices communicate within a network. The video categorizes these into several common types:
l
Common Wired Topologies:   
 
Star Topology: All devices connect to a central point, like a hub or switch. While it isolates device failures, the central hub represents a single point of failure 

Mesh Topology: Every device is connected to every other device, providing high redundancy. It is expensive due to cabling requirements and is primarily used in wide-area networks like the Internet

Point-to-Point: The simplest form, involving a direct connection between two hosts using a single cable.

Spine-Leaf Topology: A two-layer design consisting of spine and leaf switches. It minimizes latency by ensuring a maximum of two hops between any two servers, making it highly efficient for modern data centers 

Hybrid Topology: A combination of multiple topology types used to suit an organization's specific needs.

Enterprise Design Models:

Three-Tier Hierarchical Model: A Cisco blueprint for large networks consisting of three layers: Core (backbone/high-speed routing), Distribution (middleman/policies), and Access (end-user connections)

Collapsed Core Model: A two-tier variation where the core and distribution layers are combined, designed to reduce costs in smaller networks.

Traffic Flow Concepts:

East-West Traffic: Communication between machines within the same data center.

North-South Traffic: Communication between a data center and an external network.
